{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17538665","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17538665"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":1,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T17:31:22+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T17:31:22+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"16260"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"16260","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/16260"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.05,0.72,0.05,0.17,0.01]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"8951"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"64550"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"8951","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/8951"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"16260"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"49983"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"22"},{"type":"tags","id":"25"},{"type":"tags","id":"66"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"297"},{"type":"tags","id":"1318"},{"type":"tags","id":"4084"},{"type":"tags","id":"4176"},{"type":"tags","id":"4210"},{"type":"tags","id":"12801"},{"type":"tags","id":"12802"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"21294"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"64550","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/64550"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 32-year-old woman presents to the General Practice clinic with a three-month history of post-coital bleeding and intermenstrual spotting. She has no significant medical history and takes no regular medications. Her last cervical screening test was five years ago. She is a non-smoker and has had three sexual partners in her lifetime. She has never been pregnant.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn examination, she appears well with vital signs within normal limits. Speculum examination reveals a normal-appearing cervix with no obvious lesions. A cervical screening test is performed, which shows possible high-grade squamous intraepithelial lesion. Subsequent colposcopy with directed biopsy confirms cervical intraepithelial neoplasia grade 2 (CIN2).\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most appropriate management?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Observation with repeat colposcopy in six months","Large Loop Excision of the Transformation Zone","Laser ablation","Cone biopsy","Hysterectomy"],"correctOptions":[1],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis patient has biopsy-confirmed CIN2, which represents moderate cervical dysplasia. CIN2 has a significant risk of progression to higher-grade lesions and requires active management in women over 25 years of age.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ELarge Loop Excision of the Transformation Zone\u003C/strong\u003E (LLETZ) is the preferred treatment for CIN2. This procedure removes the entire transformation zone where dysplastic changes occur, allowing histological examination of the excised tissue. It can be performed under local anaesthesia and has high success rates with relatively low morbidity.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EObservation with repeat colposcopy\u003C/strong\u003E may be appropriate for young women under 25 with CIN2, as there is a high rate of spontaneous regression in this age group. However, for this 32-year-old woman, active treatment is recommended due to the risk of progression.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ELaser ablation\u003C/strong\u003E can be effective but requires specialised equipment and expertise. It is also a destructive rather than excisional technique, meaning no tissue specimen is obtained for pathological examination.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ECone biopsy\u003C/strong\u003E is more extensive than LLETZ and is typically reserved for cases where invasive cancer is suspected or when the transformation zone cannot be adequately visualised. It carries a higher risk of cervical stenosis and pregnancy complications.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EHysterectomy\u003C/strong\u003E is overly aggressive for CIN2 and would only be considered for invasive cervical cancer or persistent/recurrent high-grade lesions after conservative treatment.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EFollowing treatment, the patient should have follow-up cervical screening at 12 months. If this is negative, she can return to routine screening intervals.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Large Loop Excision of the Transformation Zone (LLETZ) is the preferred treatment for CIN2 in women over 25 years.","CIN2 represents moderate cervical dysplasia with significant risk of progression to higher-grade lesions.","Follow-up cervical screening is required at 12 months post-treatment for CIN2."],"references":["Cancer Council Australia. Treatment of HSIL [Internet]. Sydney: Cancer Council Australia; 2023 [cited 2024 Nov 23]. Available from: https://www.cancer.org.au/clinical-guidelines/cervical-cancer/cervical-cancer-screening/management-histologically-confirmed-high-grade-squamous-abnormalities/treatment-of-hsil"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"49983"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"16260"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"49983","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/49983"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-11-23T19:53:20+10:30","updatedAt":"2024-11-23T19:53:59+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"8951"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"64550"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"22","link